{"source_key":"sha256-b4cec238995b260ac54aae4fdce1a71d","record_index":207,"record_hash":"sha256:1a23d718692a2bcd278730f82ca214a3f66affbda0e6a89a0cd6e1b5d377d7f1","timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:15:40.835Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_kind":"file_edit","file_path_hashes":["3e7e73af22d0c672342a058e6394635f"],"tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agentlog-local-publishing.md\n@@\n The safer default is local-first capture plus explicit publish.\n+\n+This is consent before propagation. It is not a secrecy layer after publication:\n+once metadata has been synced to a remote, this feature should not pretend it can\n+make that data private again.\n@@\n The command should:\n \n - find the relevant local sessions and turns for that target, using the same\n   relationship logic that powers `skim` and Agent Trail\n-- include the supporting session metadata required for those turns to render\n-  correctly\n+- publish whole sessions that touched the target, not isolated turns\n - move the relevant keys from `local:gitbutler:...` to `gitbutler:...`\n - run metadata sync after a successful publish\n - support `--dry-run`, printing what would be shared without changing metadata or\n   syncing\n \n-Users who want old behavior should have an explicit opt-in. Start minimal: a CLI\n-flag or config setting is enough. The important bit is that sharing-by-default is\n-visible and intentional.\n+The dry run should give enough shape for trust without dumping raw transcript\n+content: target, session count, turn count, latest timestamps, and hints for\n+previewing the same data with `skim` / `show`.\n+\n+Local reads should remain useful for day-to-day agent context. `skim` should show\n+both local-only and published sessions, with clear status labels.\n+\n+Users who want old behavior should have an explicit per-repo opt-in. For the POC,\n+keep this deliberately small: read a manually configured `gitbutler.*` Git config\n+key. There does not need to be app UI or a first-class setter yet.\n@@\n Do not overfit the storage design before implementation. The task is to preserve\n the current public shape while adding a local-first staging step.\n \n+Do not solve full-app visibility yet. For now, unpublished/published status can\n+surface in `skim`; wider GitButler UI affordances are future work.\n+\n+Do not migrate existing already-published agentlogs back to local. Leave existing\n+published data alone and apply local-first behavior to new captures.\n+\n ## Engineering Notes\n@@\n ## Open Questions\n \n-- Should `publish` move local data or copy it and leave a local copy behind? I\n-  would pick move first: it matches the user's mental model and avoids duplicate\n-  reads.\n-- For a target match, do we publish entire sessions that touched the target, or\n-  only the matching turns plus enough context to render them? Entire sessions are\n-  simpler and less likely to produce broken context; turn-scoped publishing leaks\n-  less.\n-- Should local `skim` show local-only sessions, published sessions, or both? For\n-  day-to-day agent context, both is probably right, with a clear published/local\n-  status.\n-- Where should the share-by-default preference live first: hook flag, Git config,\n-  or GitMeta config? A hook flag is the smallest start; config is nicer once the\n-  behavior stabilizes.\n-- How should `--dry-run` report scale: key count, session count, turn count,\n-  target names, or all of the above?\n-- What migration story do we want for existing already-published agentlogs? The\n-  safest default is to leave them published and only apply local-first behavior to\n-  new captures.\n+- Should `publish` move local data or copy it and leave a local copy behind? Move\n+  still looks like the right default, but implementation may uncover a reason to\n+  keep local copies.\n+- What exact `gitbutler.*` config key should control per-repo share-by-default?\n - Does `git-meta-lib` need an atomic `MetaEdit::Remove` or prefix-move API before\n   this is pleasant and safe to implement?\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-31T12:15:40.835Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}